{"title_page": "Doordarshan", "text_new": "{{about|the Indian public service broadcaster|the terrestrial television channel|DD National|the 2020 film|Doord ki to I iiuuiarshan (film)}}\n{{short description|India's autonomous public service broadcaster}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\u0936\u093e\u0932\u0942\n{{Infobox broadcasting network\n|name         = Doordarshan\n|logo         = Doordarshan_Logo.svg\n|country      = [[India]]\n|motto        = ''Satyam Shivam Sundaram''\n|headquarters = New Delhi, Delhi\n|key_people  = [[A. Surya Prakash]], Chairperson\n|network_type = [[Terrestrial Television|Broadcast]], satellite television, Internet, [[Over-the-top media services|OTT]]\n|available    = Nationwide\n|owner        = [[Prasar Bharati]]\n|launch_date  = {{Start date and age|df=y|1959|09|15}}\n|former_names =\n|founder      = [[Government of India]] in 1959\n|past_names   = [[All India Radio]]\n|Picture format = [[576i]] ([[4:3]] [[standard-definition television|SDTV]])<br>[[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[high-definition television|HDTV]])\n|website      = {{URL|www.doordarshan.gov.in/}}\n}}\n[[File:Doordarshan Bhawan, Copernicus Marg, Delhi.jpg|thumb|alt=Building with trees and parked cars|Doordarshan Bhawan, [[Mandi House]], Copernicus Marg, Delhi]]\n\n'''Doordarshan''' (abbreviated in English as '''DD''') is an autonomous<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Govt-plans-own-channel-real-autonomy-for-Doordarshan/articleshow/17632585.cms|title=Govt plans own channel, real autonomy for Doordarshan |work=The Times of India|access-date=18 September 2017}}</ref> [[Public broadcasting|public service broadcaster]] founded by the [[Government of India]], owned by the [[Ministry of Information and Broadcasting (India)|Broadcasting Ministry of India]] and one of [[Prasar Bharati]]'s two divisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Consumer/yop6tSTK4fyVQ9vLkT4EeK/The-future-of-Doordarshan-is-on-the-block.html|title=The future of Doordarshan is on the block}}</ref> One of India's largest broadcasting organisations in [[studio]] and [[transmitter]] infrastructure, it was established on 15 September 1959.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/doordarshan-turns-57-watch-video-of-its-first-telecast-plus-7-lesser-known-facts-about-dd-lifetv/1/764901.html|title=Doordarshan turns 57; watch video of its first telecast plus 7 lesser-known facts about DD}}</ref> Doordarshan, which also broadcasts on digital terrestrial transmitters, provides television, radio, online and mobile service throughout metropolitan and regional India and overseas through the Indian Network and Radio India.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Beginnings ===\nThe channel began modestly as an experimental broadcaster in Delhi on 14 September 1959, with a small transmitter and a makeshift studio. Regular daily transmission started in 1965 as part of [[All India Radio]], with a five-minute news bulletin read by [[Pratima Puri]]. [[Salma Sultan]] joined Doordarshan in 1967, and became a news anchor.\n\n''[[Krishi Darshan]]'' debuted on Doordarshan on 26 January 1967, and is Indian television's longest running program.<ref name=\"deb2009lad\">{{Citation | title=Indian Democracy: Problems and Prospects | author=Sharmila Mitra Deb | publisher=Anthem Press, 2009 | isbn=978-81-907570-4-1 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_XFvehm9NmcC | quote=the well-known program Krishi Darshan, which started its telecast on January 26, 1967... 'informing' and 'educating' the farmers about improving agricultural productivity}}</ref>\n\nTelevision service was extended to Bombay (now [[Mumbai]]) and [[Amritsar]] in 1972. Until 1975 only seven Indian cities had television service, and Doordarshan was the country's sole television provider.\n\nTelevision service was separated from radio on 1 April 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.preservearticles.com/2012011821095/short-essay-on-development-of-television-in-india.html|title=Short essay on Development of Television in India|first=Payal|last=Kamat|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref> The All India Radio and Doordarshan were placed under the management of separate directors-general in New Delhi. In 1982, Doordarshan became a national broadcaster.\n\n=== Nationwide transmission ===\n\nNational telecasts (DD National) were introduced in 1982. [[Color television|Colour television]] began in India with the live telecast of the Independence Day speech by Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]] on 15 August of that year, followed by the colour telecast of the [[1982 Asian Games]] in Delhi.<ref>[https://scroll.in/article/680435/flashback-1982-the-asian-games-that-transformed-delhi Flashback 1982: The Asian Games that transformed Delhi]</ref><ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/1982-Colour+television+is+introduced:+Out+of+the+dark+ages/1/76371.html 1982-Colour television is introduced: Out of the dark ages]</ref> \nLive telecasts of the opening and closing ceremonies of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] were broadcast on its national channel, and DD Sports provided round-the-clock coverage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/media/entertainment/entertainment/doordarshan-to-live-telecast-london-olympics-opening-and-closing-ceremonies/articleshow/15146433.cms|title=Doordarshan to live telecast London Olympics opening and closing ceremonies|date=25 July 2012|work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 November 2014, Doordarshan director-general Vijayalaxmi Chhabra introduced a pink-and-purple colour scheme and a new slogan: ''Desh Ka Apna Channel'' (\"The country's own channel\").<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/DD-National-to-be-relaunched-as-Desh-Ka-Apna-Channel/articleshow/45155201.cms|title=DD National to be relaunched as 'Desh Ka Apna Channel'|date=15 November 2014}}</ref> Doordarshan transmitted over a network of nearly 1,400 terrestrial transmitters in 2017, with 46 studios producing TV programmes.<ref>[https://www.channellist.in/dd-free-dish/ Doordarshan Channel List (2017)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217223701/https://www.channellist.in/dd-free-dish/ |date=17 February 2017 }}. DD Free Dish Channels, 17 February 2017</ref> After the introduction of private channels Doordarshan is struggling to keep its position in the television space.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/doordarshan-a-struggle-for-relevance/1088480/|title=Doordarshan: A struggle for relevance|date=6 March 2018|website=The Financial Express|access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref> Currently Doordarshan is trying to improve its studios and programmes while its primary aim is to serve the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/indias-radio-signals-got-more-reach-in-pakistan-than-their-in-india-rathore/|title=India's radio signals got more reach in Pakistan than their in India: Rathore|last=Excelsior|first=Daily|date=7 February 2019|website=Jammu Kashmir Latest News {{!}} Tourism {{!}} Breaking News J&K|access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== {{anchor|Current channels}}Channels ==\n\nDoordarshan operates 46 Studios, it operates 21 channels: two all-India channels ([[DD National]] and [[DD News]]),<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/irregular-doordarshan-appointments-quashed/article634149.ece</ref> 17 regional satellite channels, 11 state networks, an international channel ([[DD India]]), a sports channel ([[DD Sports]]), DD Bharati, DD Urdu and DD Kisan. On DD National (DD-1), regional and local programs are carried on a time-sharing basis for terrestrial broadcasting only. DD News, launched on 3 November 2003 and replacing [[DD Metro]] (formerly known as the DD-2 entertainment channel), provides 24-hour news. These channels are relayed by all terrestrial transmitters in India. The regional-language satellite channels have two components: a regional service for a particular state (relayed by all terrestrial transmitters in the state), and additional programs in the regional language available through cable operators and DTH operators. DD Sports broadcasts sporting events of national and international importance. It is the only sports channel which telecasts rural sports such as [[kho-kho]] and [[kabbadi]].\n\nA new regional channel, [[DD Arunprabha]] (a 24/7 satellite television channel focusing on the North Eastern region) was scheduled to begin on 15 February 2018;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-modi-to-launch-new-doordarshan-channel-dd-arun-prabha-for-the-north-east-in-arunachal-pradesh-1811881|title=PM Modi To Launch New Doordarshan Channel for the North East in Arunachal Pradesh|work=NDTV.com|access-date=26 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/pm-to-launch-dd-arun-prabha-on-feb-15/articleshow/62887849.cms|title=PM to launch DD Arun Prabha on Feb 15 |work=The Times of India|access-date=26 November 2018}}</ref> however, its launch was placed on hold.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.asianage.com/india/all-india/071018/launch-of-dds-arun-prabha-put-on-hold.html|title=Launch of DD's Arun Prabha put on hold|date=7 October 2018|work=The Asian Age|access-date=26 November 2018}}</ref> DD Arunprabha was launched on 9 February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?id=359495|title=PM Modi launches DD Arun Prabha channel in Itanagar today|website=newsonair.com|access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2019, [[Prasar Bharati]] brought 11 more State DD Channels on the Satellite footprint of India through [[DD Free Dish]]. This includes five channels for Northeastern states. This will go a long way in strengthening regional cultures and fulfilling people's aspirations. These are \u2013 \n[[DD Chhattisgarh]], [[DD Goa]], [[DD Haryana]], [[DD Himachal Pradesh]], [[DD Jharkhand]],[[DD Odia]], [[DD Manipur]], [[DD Meghalaya]], [[DD Mizoram]], [[DD Nagaland]], [[DD Tripura]] and [[DD Uttarakhand]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?id=360791|title=11 more State DD Channels on Satellite footprint|work=NewsOnAIR|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/prasar-bharati-brought-11-more-state-doordarshan-channels-on-satellite-footprint-pm-modi-5618448/|title=Prasar Bharati brought 11 more state Doordarshan channels on satellite footprint: PM Modi|work=TheIndianExpress|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Channel list==\n\n=== {{anchor|National channel}}National channels ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:middle;\n!style=\"width:180pt; background:Cyan;\"|Channel\n!style=\"width:180pt; background:Red;\"|Programming\n!style=\"width:300pt; background:Cyan;\"|Language\n|-\n|[[DD National]]\n|General Entertainment\n|[[Hindi]] & [[English language|English]]\n|-\n|[[DD News]]\n|News\n|Hindi & English\n|-\n|[[DD India]]\n|News\n|English\n|-\n|[[DD Sports]]\n|Sports\n|Hindi & English\n|-\n|[[DD Bharati]]\n|Art & Cultural Infotainment\n|Hindi & English\n|-\n|[[DD Kisan]]\n|Agricultural Infotainment\n|Hindi\n|-\n|[[DD Urdu]]\n|Infotainment\n|[[Urdu]]\n|}\n\n=== {{anchor|Regional language channel}}Regional channels ===\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:middle;\n!style=\"width:180pt; background:Cyan;\"|Channel\n!style=\"width:180pt; background:Violet;\"|Language\n!style=\"width:300pt; background:Cyan;\"|Region\n|-\n|[[DD Arunprabha]]\n|Hindi & English\n|[[Arunachal Pradesh]]\n|-\n|[[DD Bangla]]\n|[[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n|[[West Bengal]]\n|-\n|[[DD Bihar]]\n|Hindi & [[Bihari language|Bihari]]\n|[[Bihar]]\n|-\n|[[DD Chandana]]\n|[[Kannada]]\n|[[Karnataka]]\n|-\n|[[DD Girnar]]\n|[[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n|[[Gujarat]]\n|-\n|[[DD Kashir]]\n|[[Kashmiri language|Kashmiri]] & [[Urdu]]\n|[[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]]\n|-\n|[[DD Madhya Pradesh]]\n|Hindi\n|[[Madhya Pradesh]]\n|-\n|[[DD Malayalam]]\n|[[Malayala